{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534031"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:41:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:41:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14886"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14886"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.14,0.63,0.11,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59184"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7577"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4384"},{"type":"tags","id":"4653"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18525"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59184","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59184"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for her first antenatal visit at eight weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. She was born in Vietnam and moved to Australia five years ago. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 22 kg/m2. Initial antenatal screening reveals she is hepatitis B surface antigen positive with normal liver function tests.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No further action required as evidence of previous infection","Commence antiviral therapy","Request hepatitis B viral load and refer to liver specialist","Repeat serology in third trimester","Arrange caesarean section for delivery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman has been found to be hepatitis B surface antigen positive on routine antenatal screening. The presence of hepatitis B surface antigen indicates current infection, either acute or chronic. Given her country of birth and normal liver function tests, this likely represents chronic hepatitis B infection acquired in childhood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequest hepatitis B viral load and refer to liver specialist\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This allows assessment of disease activity and the need for antiviral therapy during pregnancy. High viral loads (\u0026gt;200,000 IU/mL) in the third trimester increase the risk of vertical transmission despite neonatal vaccination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence antiviral therapy\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated, but this decision should be made by a liver specialist after full assessment of viral load and other markers of disease activity. Not all hepatitis B positive pregnant women require treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat serology in third trimester\u003C/strong\u003E alone is insufficient. While monitoring throughout pregnancy is important, immediate referral for specialist assessment is required to determine the need for treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further action required as evidence of previous infection\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as hepatitis B surface antigen positivity indicates current infection requiring specialist assessment and monitoring throughout pregnancy. Her infant will need hepatitis B immunoglobulin and vaccination within 12 hours of birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange caesarean section\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated. Mode of delivery should be based on standard obstetric indications as caesarean section has not been shown to reduce vertical transmission when appropriate prophylaxis is given to the infant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All pregnant women should be screened for hepatitis B surface antigen in early pregnancy.","Infants born to hepatitis B surface antigen positive mothers require hepatitis B immunoglobulin and vaccination within 12 hours of birth.","Referral to a liver specialist is indicated for pregnant women with active hepatitis B infection.","Caesarean section is not routinely recommended as it does not reduce the rate of vertical transmission when appropriate prophylaxis is given to the infant"],"references":["Australasian Society for Infectious Diseases (ASID). Management of perinatal infections. East Melbourne: ASID; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 5]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ASID-Management-of-Perinatal-Infections.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14886"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-05T15:06:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T15:06:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7577"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"